{
  "texts": [
    "However, a substantial body of work, comprising 22 papers where 8 utilize only few-shot learning and 14 explore both methods, recognizes the unique value of few-shot learning in guiding the model to generate test cases that adhere to specific formats or complex logic.",
    "The composition of these few-shot examples varies but typically falls into two categories.",
    "The first primarily provides test cases to demonstrate patterns, while the second offers complete code-test pairs to illustrate the mapping between implementation and verification.",
    "For instance, to demonstrate specific test patterns for elusive bugs, JSONTestGen [174] uses historically error-triggering test cases as highly informative examples to instruct the model on the expected structure of effective tests.",
    "A more robust strategy involves providing complete code-test pairs, which explicitly demonstrates the relationship between the method implementation and its corresponding test."
  ]
}